-- Emerging market funds take in $1.5 bln -banks cite EPFR
-- By Sujata Rao
-- Fri May 23, 2014 05:13AM EDT
-- None



LONDON, May 23 (Reuters) - Investors committed around $1.5 billion to emerging market funds over the past week, stepping up the pace of inflow, banks said on Friday, citing data from EPFR Global.

The Boston-based fund tracker, which releases data to clients late on Thursday, said the emerging equity funds that it tracks had taken $940 million in the week to May 21, more than twice the previous week's level. Funds dedicated to Russian equities however posted outflows of over $80 million, banks said. Emerging bond funds meanwhile saw their eighth consecutive week of inflows, taking in over $500 million though this was below last week's $1.2 billion. The latest figures bring year-to-date outflows from emerging equity funds tracked by EPFR to $29 billion, more than double total 2013 outflows of around $14 billion. Bond funds have shed $6.5 billion this year after outflows of $14 billion in 2013.